step.reason:
%text
Simply used the following \underline\text{standard results}

%

\begin{align}
2\cos x\cdot \cos y &= \cos \left(x+y\right) + \cos \left(x-y\right) \\
2\sin x\cdot\cos y &= \sin \left(x+y\right) + \sin \left(x-y\right) 
\end{align}

%text We know the following from the last step.
% \begin{tabular}{|c|c|} \hline & \text{Equals }\ldots \\ \hline 2\times P & \cos 13A + \cos 3A \\ \hline 2\times Q & \cos 21A + \cos 3A \\ \hline 2\times R & \sin 13A + \sin 3A \\ \hline 2\times S & \sin 21A - \sin 3A \\ \hline \end{tabular}
%text And therefore, % \begin{align} &\dfrac{2P-2Q}{2R-2S} = \dfrac{P-Q}{R-S} \\ &= \dfrac{\cos 13A + \cos 3A - (\cos 21A + \cos 3A)} {\sin 13A + \sin 3A - (\sin 21A + \sin 3A)} \\ &= \dfrac{\cos 13A - \cos 21A}{\sin 13A + \sin 21A} \end{align}

%text
Once again, we have simply applied  the 
foloowing \underline\text{standard results}.

Notice that these are simply the \underline\text{inverse}
of the results we used earlier. 

%

\begin{align}
\cos\alpha -\cos\beta = 2\sin\left( \frac{\alpha + \beta}{2} \right) &\cdot\sin\left( \frac{\beta-\alpha}{2}\right) \\
\sin\alpha +\sin\beta = 2\sin\left(\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2} \right) &\cdot\cos\left(\frac{\beta-\alpha}{2} \right) \\
\therefore \dfrac{\overbrace{\cos 13A -\cos 21A }^J}{\underbrace{\sin 13A + \sin 21A}_K} &= 
\dfrac{2\sin 17A\cdot \sin 4A}{2\sin 17A\cdot \cos 4A}\\
&= \tan 4A \text{ or }\underline{N=4}
\end{align}
